title: Without Reserve: Education matters for Brookfield Multiplex
text:
Brookfield Multiplex will build the $125 million Biological Sciences building on the Kensington campus in Randwick. Photo: Woods Bagot
Brookfield Multiplex has been appointed to build the $125 million Biological Sciences building at the University of New South Wales (UNSW) Kensington campus in Botany Street, Randwick.
David Ghannoum,​ NSW regional managing director at Brookfield Multiplex, said it was the latest project undertaken for the university in the past five years, including the $54 million University Terraces student accommodation, the $125 million Materials Science and Engineering Building and the $85 million Tyree Energy Technologies Building.
Spanning 21,730 square metres, the nine-storey Biological Sciences building will include an atrium and an upgrade of the surrounding landscape.
The Biological Sciences building represents the third stage of the regeneration and expansion of the UNSW Biomedical Precinct.
Advertisement Sunito's crowning glory
Crown Group founder Iwan Sunito​ has been announced as the 2015 Property Person of the Year by the Urban Taskforce. Fresh from the launch of the Green Square development at South Sydney, Infinity – where all 300 apartments were sold in one day – Mr Sunito's group is embarking on the new Sydney by Crown Group in Clarence Street, Sydney.
